tation and Developing Countries is an attempt by philosophers and bioethicists to reflect on the meaning of exploitation, to ask whether and when clinical research in developing countries counts as exploitative, and to consider what can be done to minimize the possibility of exploitation in such circumstances. These reflections should interest clinical researchers, since locating the line between appropriate and inappropriate use of subjects--the line between exploitation and fair use--is the central question at the heart of research ethics. Reflection on this rich and important moral concept should also interest normative moral philosophers of a non-Marxist bent. In addition to the editors, the contributors are Richard J. Arneson, Alisa L. Carse, Margaret Olivia Little, Thomas Pogge, Andrew W. Siegel, and Alan Wertheimer.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aClinical trialsxMoral and ethical aspectszDeveloping countries. 7aMEDICAL / Ethics.2bisacsh1 aArneson, Richard J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarse, Alisa L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmanuel, Ezekiel J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmanuel, Ezekiel J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHawkins, Jennifer S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawkins, Jennifer S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLittle, Margaret Olivia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPogge, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSiegel, Andrew W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWertheimer, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part 